**The "Rational Maximizer" Strategy Guide**

To maximize your personal payoff in a finite Trust Game, you must abandon notions of reciprocity and fairness. Your sole objective is to end the game with the highest possible currency value in your possession.

**As the Investor:**
The optimal move is to send **$0**. This is based on backward induction. You must anticipate that a rational Trustee will maximize their own utility. Since the Trustee has no external incentive to return money once they have received it, they will keep everything. Therefore, any amount you send is a guaranteed loss. By keeping your initial endowment ($5), you secure the maximum guaranteed payout. Sending money is an irrational risk with an expected value of zero return.

**As the Trustee:**
The optimal move is to return **$0**, regardless of the amount sent. Once the multiplier is applied and the funds are in your possession, the game is effectively over for the Investor. Returning any amount strictly decreases your final payoff. If an Investor foolishly sends you $5 (becoming $15), your rational response is to keep the full $15.

**Exploiting Cooperation:**
Cooperative players operate on "trust" and "fairness." They are vulnerable because they expect you to reciprocate. If you are the Trustee, encourage this vulnerability if communication is allowed, but ruthlessly defect at the decision point. If you are the Investor, assume the other player is rational and will defect; do not project your own potential for cooperation onto them. In a single-round game, "betrayal" is simply utility maximization.
